description.text: Part for test 2

The basic equation for the shape of this egg comes from following a point on a connecting rod near the crankshaft. The equation I came up with has 3 inputs: h = height, 0<ζ<1 is the width to height ratio (ζ = 1 is a circle), and 0<ε<1 is the Crankshaft arm to connecting rod length ratio, or "egginess" factor, such that as it nears zero, it becomes an ellipse. ζ = 0.7 and ε = 0.8 looked good to me. I then put in a third dimension and created an equation-driven curve that spirals around, and swept a shape through that curve. After this, I made a circular pattern, which looks cool to me.

title: 5 round to 2 round magazine plug/limiter for Saiga/VEPR 12 gauge

description.text:
In the state of PA, during certain times of the year, you can use a semi-auto shotgun. However, you can only have a maximum of 3 rounds loaded, including chambered. So I created this to limit my 5 round magazine to 2 rounds, to comply with the local laws. Figured someone else might find this useful. I've tested on my VEPR 12 (Saigas upgraded cousin), and it works just fine. I imagine it would be Saiga compatible too, since the magazines are ALMOST interchangeable.

The groove in the bottom slides into the groove of the spring footer, and the unit goes inbetween the springs to the bottom of the Follower. It allows for 2 rounds, and a little bit of push down room, but not enough for a 3rd round to fit, but enough for it to rack and cycle correctly. I recommend hitting the bottom groove with some hot glue, to help keep it from coming loose and rattling around.

This is a fix for the Kamenstein 4536 Perfect Tear Paper Towel Holder. Although a quick search on Amazon shows other manufacturers (Cuisinart) with the same tensioner design.               
I loved this paper towel holder when I first bought it. But after a few months of use, the internal tensioner, which is a small plastic piece, slowly started losing it's teeth. With only 4 total teeth, the loss of any causes the holder to hold no tension on the paper towels. It's been like this for a year or more. I didn't have a 3D printer when I originally diagnosed the problem. 
So if you have this great towel holder (with a huge design flaw), you can just print out replacement plastic parts.

On the bottom of the holder, there is a single nut. Remove the nut and washer. This will release the rod. 
On the bottom of the rod, you will find your rinky-dink plastic part. Probably in pieces. Use a small flat head screw driver to remove this part. It's glued down so you'll have to apply a little pressure.
Replace with your newly printed piece and reassemble.   
I chose PLA when I printed my part because it was similar in stiffness as the original part. My guess is that ABS would work but wouldn't offer as much tension.

For mounting the 808 Keychain Camera on a .625" OD tube using GoPro-style fasteners. If you don't want to use the gopro acorn nuts, you can use other nuts by heating it up with a soldering iron and pushing it into the plastic. If you want to turn it 90 degrees then insert a GoPro 90-degree link (or print one). Features USB and microSD card ports. The 2 tabs on the orange piece are for an elastic band if you wish to use one. I use #10 (.190") fasteners on mine, but other sizes will work This is a Work In Progress: 9/20/2013: It is now printed using a MakerBot Replicator 2, but I haven't had a chance to actually use it yet. So far I know that the hinge/clevis is a little tight, but that's sort of a good thing to keep it from rotating unintentionally. 9/22/2013: USB and card slots are a little out of alignment. description.text: Last year I scanned this statue using the windows desktop version of 123D Catch. It was a great scan. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:27091 Luckily I saved all the pictures I took. Now Autodesk has a new pro web app called ReCap Photo http://recap.autodesk.com (requires an Autodesk 360 subscription) I tried uploading the same photos I used last year in 123D Catch into ReCap. This resulted in an even better scan. Some features such as the cross on the chest was completely missing from the last scan. The toes in the feet are now there. And the details in the hand holding the flowers is also more detailed. (ignore the more roughly textured face - I smoothed that in meshmixer in the old scan, with this scan this is the raw output after repair in Netfabb with no touchup) ReCap seems great so far. The manual stitching seems better than the last time I tried 123D catch and works great in the web version. One less reason for me to reboot into windows! Lesson learned: Save all your old 123D catch photos. I have a feeling as better software is released over time, you'll be able to load those old photos and get even better output.

The open source portable and modular game inspired by chess. Chez is a game system based on chess. It is intended to be the most 3dprinter friendly chess set in the world. chez on github
The model for the chess pieces. This is intended to be a one color print that is printed twice.

The board is built by assembling interlocking modular 4-unit board parts. To create a basic chess board this model should be printed two times in each color. Each colored part should be fit with a part of the opposite color.
This is the main box of the chez box container. It has three areas for for internal shelves. Two piece shelves and a bottom shelve for the modular board. Print this one time in one of the two colors.
This is the top to the chez box container. Print this one time in one of the two colors.
Each set of pieces has its own shelve that can be placed inside the chez container. Print this twice in each color. These slide into the top two compartments of the container.
chez_box_r_p4 is an optional print, if you like having your board modules in their own removable container then print this one time.

Chez Basic simplifies the rules of chess, so that a common game system can be applied to multiple chess inspired games. If desired the more complex version of the gaming rules can be found Chess public domain rules on Wikipedia
The king can move exactly one square horizontally, vertically, or diagonally. Only once per player, per game.
The rook moves any number of vacant squares vertically or horizontally. It also is moved while castling.
The bishop moves any number of vacant squares in any diagonal direction.
The queen can move any number of vacant squares diagonally, horizontally, or vertically.

The knight moves to the nearest square not on the same rank, file, or diagonal. In other words, the knight moves two squares horizontally then one square vertically, or one square horizontally then two squares vertically. Its move is not blocked by other pieces: it jumps to the new location.

Pawns have the most complex rules of movement:
A pawn can move forward one square, if that square is unoccupied. If it has not yet moved, each pawn has the option of moving two squares forward provided both squares in front of the pawn are unoccupied. A pawn cannot move backwards. Pawns are the only pieces that capture differently from how they move. They can capture an enemy piece on either of the two spaces adjacent to the space in front of them (i.e., the two squares diagonally in front of them) but cannot move to these spaces if they are vacant.

comments.text: That's a nice looking chess set. I don't understand why anyone thinks it necessary to "simplify" the rules of chess, though.

comments.text: Well its difficult for some kids to grok the more complex rules like some of the special pawn rules or the castle rule. When I have introduced some of those rules to kids they have been a bit confused, so I simplified it to be the basic moves that would be used in all the games. I really want this to be a print set that a kid could use as an intro to chess.

remixed_from.title: Rod adapter for Xnaron Printable Magnetic u-joint for Rostocks

title: Xnaron Magnetic U-joint option for Rostocks

description.text:
This is a mod of the ever popular Mod for the Rostock MAXes by Xnaron. I designed a LM8UU carriage for the Rostock Mini/Rostock and any other system that works the same as these 2 printers. I have also included all of the important files for the original mod, including the original cheapskate mounts for the MAX, as well as rod adapters for the default Rostock Mini carbon fiber arms. The carriages I created have built in belt retainers that work great, as well as bolt tightened clamps for the linear bearings. http://forum.seemecnc.com/viewtopic.php?f=54&t=1704&sid=512048173d7806425ee0b8a411e75957 - The original thread (post about the jig)
This will happen if you don't get all of the arms the exact same length. Build a jig to make them like this http://www.flickr.com/photos/[email protected]/8771948345/ and http://www.flickr.com/photos/[email protected]/8771958335/ This is a WIP, I designed this in one day and printed version 1. It seems to work, but I will update and post new files if I find any problems while using this mod. Speed tests:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMixjjFxf1I
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S7NqfRLNDAg

The default setup is for 3/8 inch carbon fiber or aluminum rods, which can be substituted for 3/8 Crossbow bolts, 3/8 inch chrome steel balls, and 3/8 inch N52 Neodymium magnets. The chrome steel balls are meant to be JB welded or TIG/MIG welded to the heads of 6mm M3 capshead bolts. Be careful if you MIG or TIG weld them, you can easily melt the M3 bolt from the heat, all that is needed is a few tacks.  
For the Rostock or Rostock mini, print 2 of the boom ends, an effector, and 3 of my magnetic carriages, as well as 12 rod adapters if you have .199" OD Carbon fiber tubes for your arms (I would recommend ABS). Assemble everything according to the instructions in the SeeMeCNC forum thread, and make sure you use the jig mentioned in the description to get consistent length arms, or they can become disconnected mid print  
For the Rostock MAX print all of the same things, except for my carriages and the rod adapters, unless you want to use .199" CF arms on your MAX. Instead of the carriages, print the Cheapskate 90 degree ballends. The assembly is pretty much the same.   
It is a good idea to read some of the forum thread to get an Idea of what to do an not to do while assembling, though before screwing the balls onto anything, you should tap the hole with either an M3 tap or by forcing an M3 bolt into it. Make sure not to strip the threads you create in the plastic, this is what keeps the ballbolts secured. Also, try to avoid putting torsion strain on the JB weld, It probably will break, AKA, dont twist the balls on by hand, especially if they are resisting threading into the hole. use a small pair of needle nose pliers instead.

description.text:
I liked Thomas Sanladerer, design on his youtube review of the titan. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tiAQ9slUZ58.

So I made one to work for the Robo3D, this is for the E3DV6, but making it work for the Hexagon should be no problem, .step files are included. Basically you would recess the hole underneath more to fit the hexagon.

  • You will need this quick release as well. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1192896
  • You will need some M4 bolts and locknuts. And will probably have to dremel them to the exact length so they don't stick up.

description.text:
This is a 2V geodesic dome connector for 3/4" conduit steel tubing. The design has flashing build into it to allow the insertion of 3/8" thick panels. The panels could be made of plywood ,polycarbonate or any ridged construction material. The design has pilot holes for drilling supports, I would recommend self tapping screws for permanent installations or nuts, bolts and rubber washers for temporary structures.

Print 6 - 5 way connectors
Print 10 - 6 way connectors
Print 10 - 4 way connectors

Total: 26 printed parts

Get 35 - 10 foot length, 3/4" diameter conduit steel tubing from your favourite hardware store like home depot. You need to make 30 A poles at 56" and 35 B poles at 63.5", you should only need to cut each pole once, they can be cut with a hack saw or a metal cutting disk on a chop saw.

You will need 26 nuts and bolts and 52 washers.

Get your polycarbonate, plywood or whatever material you choose panels and cut them to size, screw them in with self tapping screws, seal the panels with caulking.

There are two size of faces:

  • A-A-B x 30
  • B-B-B x 10

Where A = 56" and B = 63.5"

Makes 17 foot Diameter Geodesic Dome, with a height of 8 foot 6 inches at the centre.

The features of this geodesic dome design over others is:

  • Panel design for cover (YAY no more tarps)
  • Electrical wiring or water lines can be run inside of poles and exit at connectors

check out https://simplydifferently.org/Geodesic_Dome_Notes?page=3#2V/L2%20Icosahedron%20Dome for more information on dome calculations.

description.text:
This is a 3D printable holder for the cheap ZTE speed Android phone, designed for use on FTC robots. With the new control system in FTC, they give us these phones, but no good way of attaching them to the robot or securing the USB cord. I designed this part to solve this problem for my former FTC team, 4278 De.Evolution. Unlike the holder in the kit-of-parts, it fits around the whole phone and locks it in place securely.

It has a USB cable strain relief (sized for the white MR OTG cable, but should fit most other cords), and holes spaced for a TETRIX beam on the side plates. It also has cutouts for the volume and power buttons, the speaker, the microphone, the camera, and the headphone jack.

This holder has several different mounting options. You can mount it to a tetrix beam using the provided holes, or you can mount it to something else by drilling your own holes wherever you want in the side plates. You can also zip tie it on, or you can use ABS cement to securely weld it to another 3D printed part (see my other phone holders).

The phone is secured by a clip at the bottom, and you need to be able to bend this clip backward to release the phone (make sure to unplug the USB cable first, or you might damage your USB port). So, you can't mount the holder with the center-bottom flush against something. You can cut a hole, mount it between beams with space in the middle, or mount it in standoffs. Or whatever else you need to do.

I'm not sure how effective this thing actually is at making the USB connection more reliable; De.Evolution had a season plagued by disconnects even with this (though there's no way to tell the cause; it could have been anything from static electricity to dying motor controllers, the new system's so unreliable). However, another team using it had much better luck. I hope it will work as some kind of counter to Qualcomm, MR/HiTechnic, and FIRST's poor design decisions.

I also included the Geomagic Design (formerly Alibre) source files (including the somewhat inaccurate phone model) in the source zip file in the downloads section. Be warned, though, the model has a tendency to crash Geomagic frequently, so save often.

While cutting a large print I had one of the belt tension zipties come lose and cause the endmill to drag an 1/8inch too low across my carving, so I looked around for a different way to keep them tight. Most of the other tension devices require you to reprint the corners, so I modified one version to fit the original corner.

Part A requires you to replace the whole top side of the corner, but Part B slips into the original Ziptie hole of the lower corner. You may have to trim the tab on Part B to fit into the original Ziptie hole, but I figured it's easier to trim off plastic than add plastic after the fact.

If you decide to use the loop bolts like I did, take note of which side of the printer has the most room when the slide goes all the way to the end (most likely the tool side). I didn't and I lost a little bit of room on the non-tool side because the slide now runs into the bolt. This is easily fixed if you put the bolt on the side with the tool. If you don't want to use loop bolts like I did, then just print 2.stl from here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1128468

If you need to flip the parts, just use the mirror function in either Cura or Repetier host.

Lastly, if you compare the photos to the STLs, they're a little different. I modified both Part A1 and Part A2 to bring the belt a little closer to the bar. I noticed when I printed the original versions they stuck out a little too far, but it doesn't really hurt anything and I don't want to waste more plastic to fix it for myself.

If you have a rare-earth magnet lying around you can print up one of these and slip it on your common LED torch and make it magnetic in under 30 minutes.
I recommend a printing a pair and using two x 3mmx10mm magnets if you are using smaller magnets it will certainly need two brackets and feel free to modify the file if you have magnets of different sizes. using 1 3mm x 10mm round magnet just holds it to the fridge.

title: Compact Bowden Extruder (Geared Motor Version) for 1.75 filament

description.text:
This is a variant of scarou's and 0110-M-P's Compact Bowden Extruder. It's been designed for use with 1.75mm filament and a Nema 17 Planetary Geared Motor with a 8mm bore hobbed drive gear.

Tolerances are very tight, so I don't know if this design can work with a different hobbed gear and/or a different geared stepper motor.
Here is the link to the ones I've used:

  • Kysan Nema 17 Geared Stepper Motor (PN 1040229)
  • Hardened Steel Hobbed Drive Gear (8mm Bore)

STEP files are included, so feel free to modify the design as you please.

  • Added Body that fits the Rostock Max V2/V1. The distance between the mounting holes is the same as the EZstruder, so it works with the stock mounting bracket.

  • Added Body with dual pushfit and no brackets. I'm currently using this one with an air extruder setup and it's been working great.

Recommended Settings:

  • Body: 0.2mm layer height or less. 30% infill or more.
  • Arms: 0.2mm layer height or less. 70% infill or more.
    Don't use PLA, the motor runs hot.

The filament path has a diameter of 1.5mm, so you must use a 2mm drill bit to make it work for 1.75mm filament.

Take a look at the pictures, there are annotations that show how to assemble the extruder. It's pretty straightforward though.

I purchased Builttospec's lighting kit for my TOM about a month ago and it works great, I just wanted to add an on/off switch to the setup. I designed a small cap to fit into the front right hole in my machine and installed a radio shack (275-011A) switch. The wires run down the front side and under the acrylic plate. 
builttospecstore.storenvy.com/products/48569-makerbot-lighting-kit-white-leds

Once printed, the button hole might need to be sanded slightly to make it fit snugly. The nut on the underside isn't super tight, but everything is so close anyways, it isn't a huge concern. Other than that, wire your LED strip's power through the switch before the 12v connector and you're done!

description.text:
This is just for fun and is not trying for movie accuracy. It is designed to sit up high inside the dome and in particular sit on the speaker that was used in the inside dome structure.

The metal part covers an adafruit neopixel part and I used two layers of lenticular material over the top of that (at 90 degree angles to each other) just to give some interesting textures.

https://youtu.be/_RfGiKQPgAs

Used one of these for the metal lens holder: "44mm Lens+Reflector Collimator+Fixed bracket For 20W 30W 50W 100W LED B81", just a few dollars on ebay. I did not like the looks of the LEDs on when using the large spherical lens, so when instead with the lenticulars.

I did print the top tow pieces in glow-in-the dark filament and had a lot of trouble getting it to print the fine parts and also not break it when detaching from the platen. The inside was some tubing I had, cut to the right length and the I wrapped transformer filament around it. Placed it inside and then glued the tow parts together.

The glow in the dark is fun, but it has to be very dark for you to notice and only when the pack is shut down (LEDs turned off).
